        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Kingston Jamaica</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <date>5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Jany. 5/23/1863</date>
            </p>
            <p>My dear <addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee>â€”</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am in receipt of<lb/> your letters of <date>Nov.</date> &amp;
                    <date>Decr.</date> and the<lb/> Occident for those months. By<lb/> this Steamer
                    <persName>Mr. Alfred Delgado</persName><lb/> of this city leaves for
                    <placeName>New York</placeName>. I have<lb/> handed him <add>?</add> sovereigns
                    <add>in gold</add> to be<lb/> delivered to you, on your applying<lb/> to
                    <persName>Messrs Henry &amp; De Cordova</persName>, at whose<lb/> office the
                money will be left. This is<lb/> all I had in hand. Perhaps a few more<lb/> copies
                (say 3 or 4) of the pirated edition,<lb/> of the Pentateuch with the
                    <date>Sabbath</date> Prayer<lb/> may obtain a sale, there having lately<lb/>
                been an inquiry for them. The question<lb/> respecting the amot. of produce raised
                in the time of slavery and of emancipation<lb/> can only be answered by reference
                to</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>statistical tables, which are not easily<lb/> procurable. On general data the
                following<lb/> may be relied onâ€”130,000 <add>?</add> Sugar were<lb/> often annually
                exported during slavery;<lb/> whereas the highest quantity shipped<lb/> annually
                since emancipation has not<lb/> exceeded 37000 <add>?</add>; and that figure<lb/>
                was only attained in <date>1862</date>, the crop having<lb/> raised between that and
                22000 <add>?</add>, the<lb/> lowest yield in <date>1855</date>. In coffee the
                falling<lb/> off has been equally great, no crop since<lb/> Emancipation having been
                higher than 6<lb/> millions of pounds, and in some years not more<lb/> than 4
                millions. Before <date>1846</date>, emancipation<lb/> having taken place in
                    <date>1834</date>, matters began<lb/> to turn in favor of the planter, when
                the<lb/> abolition of the differential duties by the<lb/> British Parliament
                depressed sugar Culitva-<lb/>tion wherever Emancipation had been established<lb/> to
                an alarming extent, whilst it proportionately<lb/> raised it wherever slavery
                existed. This<lb/> suicidal and unjust measure, a <add>?</add> to<lb/> the Free
                Trader, gave <placeName>Louisiana</placeName> and <placeName>Cuba</placeName><lb/>
                such a <add>?</add>, that cane cultivation,</p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p>which was about being abandoned in the<lb/> former, and entailed ruinous lapses on
                planters<lb/> in the latter, owing to the viability of slave<lb/>
                <del>produce</del> labor to compete with free labor when protected<lb/> by the
                differential duties,â€”began to attain that<lb/> prosperity in slave countries which
                    <del>they</del> it<lb/> has since maintained. The immense<lb/> number of small
                settlers, formerly slaves,<lb/> in this <placeName>Island</placeName>, increased by
                the abundance<lb/> and cheapness of land, has caused a dearth<lb/> of labor in the
                market, which only immigration<lb/> can supply. But colored laborers, however<lb/>
                large the number imported will not resus-<lb/> citate
                <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>. She wants a large influx<lb/> of <hi
                    rend="underline">white</hi> settlers in the beautiful and<lb/> salubrious
                mountain regions, where <hi rend="underline">whites</hi><lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">can</hi> labor without the fear of yellow fever<lb/> or other
                tropical diseases. I will write<lb/> you more on this topic on some future
                occasion.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">You and I are of the same age<lb/> it appears. I made 56 in
                    <date>Novr.</date> God<lb/> grant that the balance of your days<lb/> may be more
                happy than the first part<lb/> has been and that you may receive<lb/> Even in this
                life the reward so justly</p>
            <pb n="2V"/>
            <p>your due for your arduous labors<lb/> in the good cause. The <persName>Revd Mr.
                    Myers</persName><lb/> will address you, he has already found<lb/> he is not
                reposing on a bed of roses.<lb/> He will possibly state particulars.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your accounts of <persName>Miss Gratz</persName> are<lb/> full of
                melancholy interest. I have many<lb/> times sat down to write her, but have<lb/>
                abandoned the idea, lest any querulous<lb/> word might slip into the sheet and<lb/>
                give her pain, which I wish to avoid.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">When will this horrible war come<lb/> to an end? What is slavery,
                with all its<lb/> horrors to this inhuman and cruel<lb/> butchery which rivals in
                atrocity and<lb/> barbarity the sanguinary deeds of
                    <persName>Jamelane<add>?</add></persName><lb/> or <persName>Genghis
                    Khan</persName>? O may God soon send<lb/> peace, for it is sickening to humanity
                to<lb/> watch even at a distance the course struggle.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">With affectionate regard,<lb/> from <persName>Mrs. Nathan</persName>
                and self. (<persName>Mrs Samson</persName> is out of town)<lb/> I am</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">
                <persName role="author">MN Nathan</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="The following is written in pencil at the bottom of the page.">20-405</p>
